text: (7/7) I’m going to continue to demand accountability and transparency and fighting for the due process every person in this country is promised.

(6/7) These stories show the results of a cruel mass deportation campaign that tears families apart, overwhelms jails, and keeps people locked up without due process.

And instead of fixing this broken system, the Trump Admin wants to expand it.

(5/7) Here’s why this raises major concerns. Most states require prosecutors to file charges within 72 hours, or the person must be released. But ICE detainer agreements pressure jails to hold people until ICE arrives, often for weeks or even months on end.

(4/7) A mother of an 8-year-old is stuck in detention while her sick mother struggles to care for her child. With an ICE detainer keeping her from her family, she can’t be there to take care of her kid or her mother.

(3/7) A Haitian woman on the CHNV program with 9 months left was arrested police following a domestic violence incident. She applied for TPS & asylum, but the Trump admin canceled the program. She’d be here legally today if not for that decision.

(2/7) One woman, a former teacher, has been waiting over 12 years for asylum. She was arrested after a domestic violence incident (charges dropped) but is still detained. The conditions are so dire that she’s even asked to self-deport, but ICE hasn’t processed her request.

(1/7) I’ve been making visits to Orange County Corrections to meet with detainees. Yesterday, I met women—mothers, survivors of abuse, and some with pending cases—who have no criminal history, yet are stuck behind bars on immigration holds.

🧵 Their stories are heartbreaking:

Rumor: Funding for FEMA disaster response was diverted to support international efforts or border related issues.

Fact: This is false. No money is being diverted from disaster response needs. FEMA’s disaster response efforts and individual assistance is funded through the Disaster Relief Fund, which is a dedicated fund for disaster efforts. Disaster Relief Fund money has not been diverted to other, non-disaster related efforts.

https://t.co/Gfdt11fesK

Rumor: FEMA is blockading people in Florida and preventing evacuations.

Fact:
This is false.
FEMA is not blockading people in Florida and preventing evacuations. FEMA does not control traffic flow or conduct traffic stops, which are handled by local authorities. This is a harmful rumor that can put lives in danger.

If you live in the west coast of Florida and the Florida peninsula, take immediate action to protect yourself and your loved ones. Follow the guidance of your local authorities.

https://t.co/u5LDQmePze

Rumor: FEMA will only provide $750 to disaster survivors to support their recovery.

Fact:
This is false.
This is a type of assistance that you may be approved for soon after you apply, called Serious Needs Assistance. It is an upfront, flexible payment to help cover essential items like food, water, baby formula, breastfeeding supplies, medication and other emergency supplies. There are other forms of assistance that you may qualify for to receive and Serious Needs Assistance is an initial payment you may receive while FEMA assesses your eligibility for additional funds.

Orange County Government: County offices are closed on Wednesday, Oct. 9, and Thursday, Oct. 10.
Ninth Judicial Circuit Court of Florida: Courthouses are closed on Wednesday, Oct. 9, and Thursday, Oct. 10.

Orange County Public Schools: After-school activities are canceled on Tuesday, Oct. 8. Schools are closed on Wednesday, Oct. 9, and Thursday, Oct. 10.

LYNX: Regular LYNX transportation services will continue as scheduled until sustained winds reach 35 mph or flooding occurs. Starting 12 hours before winds are expected to reach 35 mph, ACCESS LYNX will only provide life-sustaining medical trips.
 
UCF: Campus operations and all classes will remain suspended through Friday.
 
Valencia: Valencia College will close Tuesday through Thursday. All in-person and online classes during that time will be canceled. Monday classes will continue as scheduled. Currently, campus is planning to reopen on Friday.
 
Rollins: All in-person classes & events are canceled Oct. 7-11. Residential students must evacuate campus and follow their Hurricane/Emergency Evacuation plan. The campus will close at 5 p.m. Oct. 8.
 
SunRail: SunRail service will be temporarily suspended 10/9/24 due to Milton. Updates will be provided through SunRail's website, the SunRail Alerts app, and our social media platforms.
 
District Office: Our district office is closed Wed, Oct. 9 and Thurs. Oct 10. If you need to contact our office about an urgent matter, we encourage to call our D.C. office at (202) 225-2176. 
 
Hospitals: In response to Hurricane Milton, some of AdventHealth's operations may change for the safety of their patients, loved ones and team members. All Florida AdventHealth hospitals and emergency rooms are open and following regular business hours. Please check back regularly for any changes and if appointment with a provider, please call their office for updated hours.
 
MCO: On Wednesday, at 8 a.m., commercial operations will cease at MCO. The airport will continue to monitor the hurricane's path and will post updates as they become available. Please continue to work with your airline in regards to your flight.

CENTRAL FL CLOSURES: In preparation for Hurricane Milton, government offices, schools, and transportation services will be closed during the storm. Stay informed as the storm’s timing may affect closures in your area and continue to monitor updates.

Our district office location will be closed through Thursday. If you need to contact our office about an urgent matter, we encourage to call our D.C. office at (202) 225-2176.
